13. Decision Framework: Kameron vs Claude Code
What Kameron Decides (Human Judgment Required)
  • Product direction — what to build next, what to cut
  • Design feel — 'this doesn't feel right' is valid feedback, act on it
  • User conversations — who to reach out to, what to ask
  • Pricing decisions — when to charge, how much
  • Brand voice — how Chirp.bet talks to users
  • Go/no-go on shipping — when it's good enough to deploy
What Claude Code Decides (Technical Execution)
  • Code architecture — file structure, component patterns, API design
  • Bug fixes — find and fix without asking
  • Refactoring — clean up code, optimize performance
  • Dependency management — package choices, version updates
  • Database schema changes — propose and implement
  • Git workflow — branching, PRs, commits (via GitHub MCP)
RULE: If Kameron starts a new design iteration when the current build isn't deployed, Claude Code should push back and ask: 'Should we ship what we have first?'
RULE: If Kameron asks for infrastructure/tooling/organization work, Claude Code should ask: 'Does this directly lead to a user seeing the product?' If not, defer it.

